    <!-- When creating a new activity, make a copy of this file with appropriate name -->
    <worksheet margin="1in" bottom="1.25in" xml:id="ws-area">
      <title>Worksheet for Section 7.1</title>

      <objectives>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              Find the area of Type 1 regions bounded by curves
              in the plane.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Find the area of Type 2 regions bounded by curves
              in the plane.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </objectives>


      <page>
        <exercise workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p> Find the area bounded by the curves <m>y = -x</m> and <m>y = 2-x^2</m>. (Hint: you
              first need to find where the curves intersect.) </p>
          </statement>

          <solution>
            <p>See <xref ref="fig-ws-area-ex1-sol" /> for a diagram. The two curves intersect when <me>-x
              = 2-x^2 \iff x^2 - x - 2 = 0 \iff (x+1)(x-2) =
                0</me> So <m>x=-1</m> or <m>x=2</m>. </p>

            <figure xml:id="fig-ws-area-ex1-sol">
              <image width="61.8%">
                <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org"
                  label="fig-ws-area-ex1-sol-fig">
                  <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                    <definition>NyuViolet="#57068c"</definition>
                    <definition>UltraViolet="8900e1"</definition>
                    <definition>MediumViolet1="#702b9d"</definition>
                    <definition>MediumViolet2="#7b5aa6"</definition>
                    <definition>LightViolet1="#ab82c5"</definition>
                    <definition>LightViolet2="#eee6f3"</definition>
                    <definition>f(x)=2-x^2</definition>
                    <definition>g(x)=-x</definition>
                    <definition>a = -1</definition>
                    <definition>b = 2 </definition>
                    <coordinates bbox="(-2.2,-2.2,3.2,3.2)">
                      <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y" />
                      <graph at="graph" function="f" />
                      <graph at="line" function="g" />
                      <area-between-curves functions="(f,g)" domain="(a,b)" />
                      <point at="point" p="(a,f(a))" />
                      <point at="point" p="(b,f(b))" />
                    </coordinates>
                  </diagram>
                </prefigure>
              </image>
            </figure>

            <p> The area is <me>\int_{-1}^2 \left((2-x^2)-(-x)\right)\,dx = \frac{9}{2}.</me>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise workspace="1in">
          <task workspace="">
            <statement>
              <p> Draw the region bounded by the curves <m>y=x</m> and <m>x=y^2 -2</m>. </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p> See <xref ref="fig-ws-area-ex2-sol" />. </p>
              <figure xml:id="fig-ws-area-ex2-sol">
                <image width="61.8%">
                  <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org"
                    label="fig-ws-area-ex2-sol-fig">
                    <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                      <definition>NyuViolet="#57068c"</definition>
                      <definition>UltraViolet="8900e1"</definition>
                      <definition>MediumViolet1="#702b9d"</definition>
                      <definition>MediumViolet2="#7b5aa6"</definition>
                      <definition>LightViolet1="#ab82c5"</definition>
                      <definition>LightViolet2="#eee6f3"</definition>
                      <definition>f1(x)=-sqrt(x+2)</definition>
                      <definition>f2(x)= sqrt(x+2)</definition>
                      <definition>g(x)=x</definition>
                      <definition>a = -2</definition>
                      <definition>c = -1</definition>
                      <definition>b = 2</definition>
                      <coordinates bbox="(-3.2,-3.2,2.2,2.2)">
                        <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y" />
                        <area-between-curves functions="(f1,f2)" domain="(a,c)" stroke="None" />
                        <area-between-curves functions="(g,f2)" domain="(c,b)" stroke="None" />

                        <graph function="f1" domain="(-2,3)" />
                        <graph function="f2" domain="(-2,3)" />
                        <graph function="g" domain="(-3,3)" />

                        <point p="(-1,-1)" />
                        <point p="(2,2)" />
                      </coordinates>
                    </diagram>
                  </prefigure>
                </image>
              </figure>
            </solution>
          </task>
          <task workspace="">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Find the area by dividing the region into two regions where the top and bottom are
                an algebraic function and integrating.
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p> The curves intersect when <me>y^2 - 2 = y \implies y=-1,2 \implies x=-1,2</me>
                (since one of the curves is <m>y=x</m>). So to integrate in the <m>x</m> direction
                we need to divide up the region into two pieces: </p>

              <p>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <p> Region <m>R_1</m>, which is bounded by <m>y=\sqrt{x+2}</m>, <m>y=-\sqrt{x+2}</m>
                      , <m>x=-2</m>, and <m>x=-1</m>
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p> Region <m>R_2</m>, which is bounded by <m>y=\sqrt{x+2}</m>, <m>y=x</m>, <m>
                      x=-1</m>, and <m>x=1</m>. </p>
                  </li>

                </ul>
              </p>

              <p> The area of the full region is the sum of the areas of <m>R_1</m> and <m>R_2</m>: <me>\int_{-2}^{-1}
                \left[\sqrt{x+2} - \left(-\sqrt{x+2}\right)\right]\,dx + \int_{-1}^2
                  \left(\sqrt{x+2} - x\right)\,dx
                  = \frac{4}{3} + \frac{19}{6} = \frac{9}{2}</me> Notice that we get the same answer
                as in problem 1, mainly because the region here is a rotation of the region in that
                problem. </p>
            </solution>
          </task>
          <task workspace="">
            <statement>
              <p> Now find the same area by slicing <em>horizontally</em> instead of vertically;
                that is, write <m>x</m> as a function of <m>y</m> and integrate against <m>dy</m>. </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p> If we slice horizontally, the strip at level <m>y</m> has width <m>y-(y^2-2)</m>,
                and we integrate from <m>y=-1</m> to <m>y=2</m>. Thus we get <me>\int_{-1}^2
                \left(y-(y^2-2)\right)\,dy
                  = \frac{9}{2}</me> This time we get not only the same answer as in problem 1, but
                the exact same integral with <m>x</m> changed to <m>y</m>. </p>
            </solution>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Compare and contrast the two answers and the solutions.
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p>
                The answers are the same (which gives us confidence that we are correct).
                The second method involves only one integral.
              </p>
            </solution>
          </task>
        </exercise>

        <exercise workspace="1in">
          <task workspace="">
            <statement>
              <p> Draw graphs of <m>y = \sin x</m> and <m>y = \cos x</m> on the same set of axes,
                say from <m>x = 0</m> to <m>x = 4\pi</m>. </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p> See <xref ref="fig-ws-area-ex3-sol" />. </p>
              <figure xml:id="fig-ws-area-ex3-sol">
                <image width="61.8%">
                  <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org"
                    label="fig-ws-area-ex3-sol-fig">
                    <diagram dimensions="(300,100)" margins="5">
                      <definition>NyuViolet="#57068c"</definition>
                      <definition>UltraViolet="8900e1"</definition>
                      <definition>MediumViolet1="#702b9d"</definition>
                      <definition>MediumViolet2="#7b5aa6"</definition>
                      <definition>LightViolet1="#ab82c5"</definition>
                      <definition>LightViolet2="#eee6f3"</definition>
                      <definition>f(x)=sin(x)</definition>
                      <definition>g(x)=cos(x)</definition>
                      <definition>a = -2</definition>
                      <definition>c = -1</definition>
                      <definition>b = 2</definition>
                      <coordinates bbox="(0,-1,4*pi,1)">
                        <grid-axes h-pi-format="yes" xlabel="x" ylabel="y" />
                        <area-between-curves functions="(f,g)" domain="(pi/4,5*pi/4)" stroke="None" />
                        <graph function="f" domain="(0,4*pi)" />
                        <graph function="g" domain="(0,4*pi)" />
                      </coordinates>
                    </diagram>
                  </prefigure>
                </image>
              </figure>
            </solution>
          </task>
          <task workspace="">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Notice that the curves bound a certain blob which gets repeated over and over again.
                (Every second blob is flipped horizontally.)
              </p>
              <p> Find the area of one of the blobs.
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p> The curves intersect when <m>x=\frac{\pi}{4}</m> plus any multiple of <m>\pi</m>.
                So the area of the first full blob is <me>\int_{\pi/4}^{5\pi/4}\left(\sin(x) -
                \cos(x)\right)\,dx = 2 \sqrt{2}.</me>
              </p>
            </solution>
          </task>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p> Find the area bounded by the graph of <m>y = \ln x</m>, and a line joining the two
              points <m>(1, 0)</m> and <m>(e^2, 2)</m> on the curve. </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p> See <xref ref="fig-ws-area-ex4-sol" />. </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-ws-area-ex4-sol">
              <image width="61.8%">
                <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org"
                  label="fig-ws-area-ex4-sol-fig">
                  <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                    <definition>NyuViolet="#57068c"</definition>
                    <definition>UltraViolet="8900e1"</definition>
                    <definition>MediumViolet1="#702b9d"</definition>
                    <definition>MediumViolet2="#7b5aa6"</definition>
                    <definition>LightViolet1="#ab82c5"</definition>
                    <definition>LightViolet2="#eee6f3"</definition>
                    <definition>f(x)=ln(x)</definition>
                    <definition>g(x)=(2/(exp(2)-1))*(x-1)</definition>
                    <coordinates bbox="(0,-1,10,3)">
                      <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y" />
                      <area-between-curves functions="(f,g)" domain="(1,exp(2))" stroke="None" />
                      <graph function="f" domain="(0,10)" />
                      <graph function="g" domain="(0,10)" />
                      <point p="(1,0)" alignment="n">
                        <m>(1,0)</m>
                      </point>
                      <point p="(exp(2),2)" alignment="n">
                        <m>(e^2,2)</m>
                      </point>
                    </coordinates>
                  </diagram>
                </prefigure>
              </image>
            </figure>

            <p> The line connecting <m>(1,0)</m> and <m>(e^2,2)</m> has slope <m>\frac{2}{e^2-1}</m>
              and equation <me>y = \frac{2}{e^2-1}(x-1)</me> So the area between the two is <me>\int_{1}^{e^2}\left[\ln(x)
              - \left(\frac{2}{e^2-1}(x-1)\right)\right]\,dx = 2</me> On the other hand, we could go
              vertically. Then the curve has equation <m>x=e^{y}</m> and the line has equation <m>x
                = \frac{e^2-1}{2}y + 1</m>. The area is <me>\int_{0}^{2} \left[\frac{e^2-1}{2}y + 1
                -
                e^y\right]\,dy = 2</me> The <m>y</m> integral eliminates the need to do integration
              by parts to find <m>\int \ln x\,dx</m>. </p>

            <p> On the third hand, we could simplify our integration this way. Let <m>R_1</m> be the
              region bounded by <m>y=\ln x</m>, <m>y=0</m>, <m>x=1</m>, and <m>x=e^2</m>. Let <m>R_2</m>
              be the triangle with vertices <m>(1,0)</m>, <m>(e^2,0)</m>, and <m>(e^2,2)</m>. Notice <m>
              R_2</m> is contained in <m>R_1</m>, and the region <m>R</m> we want to find the area
              of is the set of points in <m>R_1</m> that are not in <m>R_2</m>. So the area of <m>R</m>
              is the area of <m>R_1</m> minus the area of <m>R_2</m>. </p>

            <p> The area of <m>R_2</m> can be calculated using geometry: it is <m>\frac{1}{2}
                (e^2-1) \cdot 2 = e^2-1</m>. The area of <m>R_1</m> is <me>\begin{aligned}
                \int_1^2 \ln x \,dx &amp;= \left[x \ln x - x\right]^{e^2}_{1} \\
                &amp;= \left[(e^2 \ln e^2 - e^2) - (1 \ln 1 - 1)\right] \\
                &amp;= 2e^2 - e^2 +1 = e^2 + 1
                \end{aligned}</me> So the area of <m>R</m> is <m>e^2 + 1 - (e^2 - 1) = 2</m>. </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Suppose two circles of radius 2 are drawn with the center of each circle on the edge
              of the other circle. What is the total area enclosed by both circles?
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p> Place the circles so that the center of one is at <m>(0,0)</m> and the center of the
              other is at <m>(2,0)</m>. See <xref ref="fig-ws-area-ex5-sol" />. </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-ws-area-ex5-sol">
              <image width="61.8%">
                <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org"
                  label="fig-ws-area-ex5-sol-fig">
                  <diagram dimensions="(300,225)" margins="5">
                    <definition>NyuViolet="#57068c"</definition>
                    <definition>UltraViolet="8900e1"</definition>
                    <definition>MediumViolet1="#702b9d"</definition>
                    <definition>MediumViolet2="#7b5aa6"</definition>
                    <definition>LightViolet1="#ab82c5"</definition>
                    <definition>LightViolet2="#eee6f3"</definition>
                    <definition>f(x)=ln(x)</definition>
                    <definition>g(x)=(2/(exp(2)-1))*(x-1)</definition>
                    <coordinates bbox="(-3,-3,5,3)">
                      <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y" />
                      <define-shapes>
                        <circle at="A" center="(0,0)" radius="2" />
                        <circle at="B" center="(2,0)" radius="2" />
                      </define-shapes>

                      <shape shapes="A,B" operation="intersection"
                        fill="LightViolet1" fill-opacity="0.5" />
                      <shape shape="A" stroke="NyuViolet" />
                      <shape shape="B" stroke="NyuViolet" />
                      <point p="(1,sqrt(3))" />
                      <point p="(1,-sqrt(3))" />
                    </coordinates>
                  </diagram>
                </prefigure>
              </image>
            </figure>

            <p> Using the symmetry we see that the area enclosed by both circles is <m>4\int_{-2}^{1}
              \sqrt{4-x^2}\,dx</m>. Let <m>x=2\Sin{\theta}</m> so that <m>\sqrt{4-x^2} = 2
              \cos{\theta}</m> and <m>dx=2\cos{\theta}\,d\theta</m>. We have <me>\begin{split}
              4\int_{-2}^{1} \sqrt{4-x^2}\,dx
                &amp;= 4 \int_{\sin^{-1}(-1)}^{\sin^{-1}(1/2)} (2 \cos{\theta}) (2 \cos{\theta}
              \,d\theta) \\
                &amp;= 16 \int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/6} \cos^2 \theta \,d\theta \\
                &amp;= 8 \int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/6} \left(1+\cos{2\theta}\right) \,d\theta \\
                &amp;= 8 \left[\theta + \frac{1}{2} \Sin{2\theta}\right]_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/6} \\
                &amp;= 8 \left[\frac{\pi}{6}-\left(-\frac{\pi}{2}\right)\right]
                + 4 \left[\Sin{2\cdot\frac{\pi}{6}} - \Sin{2\cdot-\frac{\pi}{2}}\right] \\
                &amp;= 8 \left[\frac{2\pi}{3}\right]
                + 4 \left[\Sin{\frac{\pi}{3}} - \Sin{-\pi}\right] \\
                &amp;= \frac{16\pi}{3} + 4 \cdot \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\\
                &amp;= \frac{16 \pi }{3} + 2\sqrt{3}
                \end{split}</me>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>
      </page>
